        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Direct marketing vs inbound marketing</h2>
        <p>They are opposite motions. Direct pushes; inbound pulls. Both are legitimate &mdash; the choice depends on the funnel stage.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Direct marketing (push)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Brand initiates the conversation</li>
              <li>Fast measurable response</li>
              <li>Requires a list or an audience to reach</li>
              <li>Fatigues over time without segmentation</li>
              <li>Best for retention, cross-sell, and reactivation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Inbound marketing (pull)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Customer initiates the conversation</li>
              <li>Slower to compound, longer half-life</li>
              <li>Builds an owned audience over time</li>
              <li>Requires investment in SEO or content</li>
              <li>Best for top of funnel and net-new discovery</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 direct marketing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Segment ruthlessly.</strong> A message written for everyone lands with no one. Split by behaviour, lifecycle stage, or purchase history.</li>
          <li><strong>One CTA per send.</strong> Every send answers the question "what should the reader do next?" Only one answer allowed.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure before you optimise.</strong> Track response rate, conversion rate, and revenue per send before touching creative.</li>
          <li><strong>Test one thing at a time.</strong> Subject line OR offer OR segment &mdash; never all three at once.</li>
          <li><strong>Review performance monthly.</strong> Not quarterly. Direct-response feedback loops are fast enough to reward monthly optimisation.</li>
          <li><strong>Automate the repeatable.</strong> Welcome, cart-abandon, and reactivation sequences run themselves once built.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake &mdash; sending to the whole list</div>
          <p>Batch-and-blast to a whole list looks efficient but is the single biggest source of unsubscribes and deliverability damage. Segment first, then send. If a subscriber has never opened your last 10 emails, they should not receive the 11th.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common direct marketing mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buying lists</strong> &mdash; damages sender reputation and rarely converts.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring deliverability</strong> &mdash; the best campaign fails if it lands in spam.</li>
          <li><strong>Weak or absent CTAs</strong> &mdash; direct marketing without a specific ask is just noise.</li>
          <li><strong>Same message to every segment</strong> &mdash; kills response rate and increases churn.</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking revenue attribution</strong> &mdash; without revenue-per-send, you optimise on the wrong metrics.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc pairs your direct marketing with a compounding organic content engine &mdash; publishing 30 SEO-optimised articles a month to grow the owned audience your direct-response campaigns then convert. The list, offer, and creative are yours; we make sure the list keeps growing.</p>

